901:      * <p>
902:      * Some transactional send errors cannot be resolved with a call to {@link #abortTransaction()}.  In particular,
903:      * if a transactional send finishes with a {@link ProducerFencedException}, a {@link org.apache.kafka.common.errors.OutOfOrderSequenceException},
904:      * a {@link org.apache.kafka.common.errors.UnsupportedVersionException}, or an
905:      * {@link org.apache.kafka.common.errors.AuthorizationException}, then the only option left is to call {@link #close()}.
906:      * Fatal errors cause the producer to enter a defunct state in which future API calls will continue to raise
907:      * the same underlying error wrapped in a new {@link KafkaException}.
908:      * </p>
909:      * <p>
910:      * It is a similar picture when idempotence is enabled, but no <code>transactional.id</code> has been configured.
911:      * In this case, {@link org.apache.kafka.common.errors.UnsupportedVersionException} and
912:      * {@link org.apache.kafka.common.errors.AuthorizationException} are considered fatal errors. However,
913:      * {@link ProducerFencedException} does not need to be handled. Additionally, it is possible to continue
914:      * sending after receiving an {@link org.apache.kafka.common.errors.OutOfOrderSequenceException}, but doing so
915:      * can result in out of order delivery of pending messages. To ensure proper ordering, you should close the
916:      * producer and create a new instance.
917:      * </p>
918:      * <p>
919:      * If the message format of the destination topic is not upgraded to 0.11.0.0, idempotent and transactional
920:      * produce requests will fail with an {@link org.apache.kafka.common.errors.UnsupportedForMessageFormatException}
921:      * error. If this is encountered during a transaction, it is possible to abort and continue. But note that future
922:      * sends to the same topic will continue receiving the same exception until the topic is upgraded.
923:      * </p>
924:      * <p>
